<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-PSs0wgmeN58jsI-ahRB4-w" name="prcnt_baseline_no_chng_request,_o7xRAOzzEd-EDJ0_bNhNug" guid="-PSs0wgmeN58jsI-ahRB4-w" changeDate="2010-11-15T17:14:55.250-0700" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Percentage of Baselines without Change Requests provides evidence of the&amp;nbsp;team's configuration and change&#xD;
    management processes&amp;nbsp;and can be used to monitor improvement over time.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Changes to a configuration item in a given baseline must be associated with a change request (e.g. enhancement request&#xD;
    or defect). This makes it possible to determine which baseline implements a change, and to identify which changes are&#xD;
    part of a particular baseline.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Definition&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Count the number of baselines that have no associated change requests. Divide this number by the total number of&#xD;
    baselines created.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Analysis&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A good way to monitor this metric across iterations is with a bar chart. Plot the percentage on the Y axis and&#xD;
    iterations on the X axis.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Expected trend&lt;/strong> - As the project progresses, all baselines should have associated change requests.&#xD;
    Therefore the percentage should remain at zero. An early baseline could reflect only new development (no change&#xD;
    requests).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the Percentage of Baselines without Change Requests is greater than 0%, the team must identify why changes are being&#xD;
    implemented without traceability to change requests. Either the change management process is disconnected from the&#xD;
    configuration management process, or the team is not following change and configuration management processes at all.&#xD;
    Corrective action is needed or the team will not be able to identify which requested changes are implemented in which&#xD;
    baselines.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Frequency and reporting&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    During the course of the project, baselines are created routinely for minor milestones, at the end of iterations, and&#xD;
    at major milestones associated with the end of project lifecycle phases. Monitor this metric&amp;nbsp;at the end of each&#xD;
    iteration&amp;nbsp;to confirm the team is following the configuration management process and that all baselines have&#xD;
    associated change requests.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Collection and reporting tools&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    ClearCase configuration management data can be linked to change request data in IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; ClearQuest&amp;reg; to identify&#xD;
    and report on&amp;nbsp;change requests associated with baseline changes.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A custom report can be defined to report on IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Team Concert&amp;reg; configuration and change&amp;nbsp;request work&#xD;
    item&amp;nbsp;data.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
